    id: "lit-2", subjectId: "literacy", emoji: "📖", readMins: 8,
    title: "Reading Simple Sentences",
    summary: "Reading simple sentences is one of the most exciting milestones in a young learner's journey. It is the moment when individual letters and sounds come together to form words, and words come together to carry real meaning. A sentence is not just a collection of words placed side by side—it is a complete thought that communicates something clearly to the reader. Understanding how sentences work is the foundation of all reading and writing.\n\nEvery sentence follows a set of important rules. It must begin with a capital letter, which signals to the reader that a new thought is starting. It must end with a punctuation mark—a full stop for statements, a question mark for questions, or an exclamation mark for strong feelings. These rules are not arbitrary; they exist to help readers navigate text smoothly and understand the writer's intention.\n\nA sentence has two essential parts: the subject and the predicate. The subject tells us who or what the sentence is about. The predicate tells us what the subject is doing or what is happening. In the sentence 'The bird sings,' 'the bird' is the subject and 'sings' is the predicate. Recognizing these two parts helps learners both understand what they read and construct their own clear sentences.\n\nWhen learners first begin reading sentences, they often read word by word, pausing at each one. With practice, they begin to read in phrases—groups of words that belong together—which makes reading feel more natural and fluent. Fluency is the ability to read smoothly, at a good pace, and with expression. It is a sign that the reader truly understands what they are reading.\n\nContext clues are another powerful tool for reading. When a learner encounters an unfamiliar word, they can look at the words around it to guess its meaning. For example, in the sentence 'The enormous elephant splashed in the river,' even if a child does not know the word 'enormous,' the image of an elephant gives a strong clue that it means very big. Using context clues builds vocabulary and reading independence.\n\nRe-reading is a strategy that strong readers use regularly. If a sentence does not make sense the first time, reading it again—sometimes more slowly—often reveals the meaning. Good readers also ask themselves questions as they read: Who is this about? What is happening? Why did that happen? These questions keep the mind engaged and improve comprehension.\n\nPictures and illustrations in books are valuable reading aids, especially for young learners. They provide visual context that supports understanding of the text. A picture of a child running alongside the sentence 'She runs fast' reinforces the meaning of both the words and the action. Over time, learners rely less on pictures and more on the words themselves as their reading skills grow.\n\nReading simple sentences every day builds stamina and confidence. The more a learner reads, the more familiar words become, and the faster they can decode new ones. Reading also exposes learners to new vocabulary, sentence structures, and ideas that enrich their thinking and communication. In this way, reading simple sentences is not just a skill—it is the beginning of a lifelong love of learning.",
