    id: "lit-3", subjectId: "literacy", emoji: "✍️", readMins: 8,
    title: "Creative Writing",
    summary: "Creative writing is one of the most powerful and joyful forms of human expression. It is the art of using words to create something new—a story, a poem, a diary entry, a description, or even a play. Unlike other forms of writing that follow strict rules, creative writing invites the writer to use their imagination freely. There are no wrong ideas in creative writing, and every learner has something unique and valuable to say.\n\nAt its heart, creative writing is about storytelling. Humans have told stories since the beginning of time—around fires, through songs, in paintings, and now in books. Stories help us make sense of the world, share our experiences, and connect with others. When a young learner writes a story about a brave lion or a magical tree, they are participating in this ancient and beautiful tradition of storytelling.\n\nGood creative writing begins with planning. Before putting pen to paper, a writer should think about the key elements of their piece: Who are the characters? Where does the story take place? What problem or adventure will unfold? What will happen at the end? A simple story map—a drawing or a few notes—helps the writer stay focused and ensures the story has a clear beginning, middle, and end.\n\nDescribing words, known as adjectives, are the secret ingredient that makes creative writing come alive. Instead of writing 'a house,' a creative writer might write 'a crumbling old house with broken windows and a creaking door.' Instead of 'she walked,' they might write 'she tiptoed nervously.' These details help the reader see, hear, and feel exactly what the writer imagines. The more vivid the description, the more powerful the writing.\n\nDialogue—the words that characters say to each other—is another tool that brings stories to life. When characters speak, the story feels real and dynamic. Dialogue reveals personality, moves the plot forward, and keeps the reader engaged. Learning to write dialogue correctly, with speech marks and new lines for each speaker, is an important skill in creative writing.\n\nPoetry is another exciting form of creative writing. Poems use rhythm, rhyme, and carefully chosen words to express feelings and ideas in a compact and musical way. Even young learners can write beautiful poems about things they love—rain, animals, their family, or their dreams. Poetry teaches learners to pay close attention to the sounds and meanings of words.\n\nRevision is an important part of the creative writing process. After writing a first draft, a good writer reads it back and asks: Does it make sense? Are there better words I could use? Is the story exciting? Making improvements to a first draft is not a sign of failure—it is what all professional writers do. Every great book started as a rough first draft.\n\nCreative writing builds confidence, vocabulary, and critical thinking. It gives learners a voice and teaches them that their ideas matter. Whether writing a two-sentence story or a full adventure tale, every act of creative writing is a step toward becoming a more expressive, thoughtful, and capable communicator. The habit of writing creatively, started young, can last a lifetime.",
