    id: "math-3", subjectId: "mathematics", emoji: "➖", readMins: 8,
    title: "Subtraction",
    summary: "Subtraction is the mathematical operation of taking away, and it is one of the most practical skills in everyday life. Every time we spend money and want to know how much is left, share food and need to know what remains, or count down to an event, we are using subtraction. Understanding subtraction deeply—not just as a procedure but as a concept—is essential for mathematical fluency and real-world problem solving.\n\nSubtraction can be understood in three different ways. The first is 'taking away'—removing objects from a group to find what remains. If there are 9 birds on a branch and 4 fly away, subtraction tells us that 5 remain. The second is 'finding the difference'—comparing two groups to see how many more one has than the other. The third is 'counting back'—starting at a number and moving backward. All three interpretations are valid and useful in different situations.\n\nThe language of subtraction is important. The number we start with is called the minuend. The number we take away is called the subtrahend. The answer is called the difference. The minus sign (−) tells us to subtract. When a word problem says 'how many are left,' 'how many more,' or 'what is the difference,' it is asking for subtraction.\n\nCounting back on a number line is one of the most visual and reliable strategies for subtraction. Starting at the larger number and jumping backward by the smaller number shows subtraction as movement in the decreasing direction. This visual representation helps learners understand that subtraction is the opposite of addition—while addition moves forward, subtraction moves backward.\n\nFact families reveal the beautiful relationship between addition and subtraction. Every addition fact has two related subtraction facts. If 5 + 4 = 9, then 9 − 4 = 5 and 9 − 5 = 4. These three facts form a fact family. Understanding fact families means that knowing addition facts automatically gives you subtraction facts too. This connection makes both operations easier to learn and remember.\n\nMental subtraction strategies make calculation faster. 'Counting up' is a powerful strategy—instead of counting back from 12 to find 12 − 7, count up from 7 to 12: 8, 9, 10, 11, 12—that is 5 jumps, so the answer is 5. This strategy is especially useful when the two numbers are close together. Another strategy is using known number bonds: if you know 6 + 4 = 10, you instantly know 10 − 6 = 4.\n\nSubtraction with larger numbers requires an understanding of place value. When subtracting two-digit numbers, learners must work with tens and ones separately, sometimes 'borrowing' or 'regrouping' from the tens column when the ones digit is too small. This process reinforces place value understanding and prepares learners for more complex arithmetic.\n\nSubtraction is used constantly in real life—calculating change when shopping, measuring how much further to travel, working out how many days until a birthday, or figuring out how many more points are needed to win a game. A learner who is confident with subtraction has a powerful tool for navigating the numerical world. Mastery of subtraction, built on a solid understanding of addition, sets the stage for multiplication, division, and all future mathematical learning.",
