    summary: "Measurement is the process of finding the size, amount, or degree of something using a standard unit. It is one of the most practical branches of mathematics, used in virtually every aspect of daily life. When a cook measures flour for a recipe, when a tailor measures fabric for a dress, when a doctor measures a patient's height and weight, or when a builder measures the length of a wall—all of these activities rely on the principles of measurement.\n\nLength is the measurement of how long, tall, or wide something is. We measure length using units like millimetres (mm), centimetres (cm), metres (m), and kilometres (km). A ruler measures in centimetres and millimetres. A tape measure is used for longer distances. Understanding that 10 mm = 1 cm, 100 cm = 1 m, and 1000 m = 1 km helps learners convert between units and choose the most appropriate one for any given measurement.\n\nBefore standard units were invented, people used non-standard units like hand spans, foot lengths, and arm spans to measure things. While these were useful, they were inconsistent—a hand span varies from person to person. The invention of standard units meant that measurements could be shared and compared reliably across different people and places. This is why standard units are so important in science, trade, and everyday life.\n\nWeight is the measurement of how heavy something is. We measure weight in grams (g) and kilograms (kg). A feather weighs just a few grams, while a bag of sugar weighs about 1 kilogram. Knowing that 1000 g = 1 kg helps learners work with weight in practical situations like cooking and shopping. Scales and balances are the tools used to measure weight accurately.\n\nCapacity is the measurement of how much liquid a container can hold. We measure capacity in millilitres (ml) and litres (l). A teaspoon holds about 5 ml, a cup holds about 250 ml, and a large water bottle holds 1 litre. Knowing that 1000 ml = 1 l is essential for cooking, medicine, and science. Measuring jugs and cylinders are used to measure liquid capacity.\n\nTime is also a form of measurement. We measure time in seconds, minutes, hours, days, weeks, months, and years. Reading a clock—both analogue and digital—is a measurement skill that learners use every day. Understanding the relationship between units of time (60 seconds = 1 minute, 60 minutes = 1 hour, 24 hours = 1 day) is essential for planning, scheduling, and understanding the world.\n\nEstimation is an important part of measurement. Before measuring precisely, a good mathematician makes an estimate—an educated guess about the likely measurement. Estimation develops number sense and helps learners check whether their precise measurements are reasonable. If a learner estimates that a pencil is about 15 cm long and then measures it to be 14.5 cm, they know their measurement is likely correct.\n\nMeasurement connects mathematics to science, cooking, construction, health, and countless other fields. Every time a learner measures something—whether with a ruler, a scale, a measuring jug, or a clock—they are applying mathematical thinking to the real world. Developing strong measurement skills from an early age gives learners a practical toolkit that they will use every day for the rest of their lives.",
