    title: "Nouns and Verbs",
    summary: "Nouns and verbs are the two most essential building blocks of the English language. Every sentence, no matter how simple or complex, is built around these two word types. A noun names something—a person, place, animal, or thing. A verb describes an action or a state of being. Together, a noun and a verb form the core of every sentence, and understanding them deeply is the foundation of all grammar knowledge.\n\nNouns are the naming words of language. They give names to everything we can see, touch, think about, or imagine. Common nouns name general things: dog, school, book, city, happiness. Proper nouns name specific, unique things and always begin with a capital letter: Nairobi, Monday, Kenya, Amina. Collective nouns name groups: a flock of birds, a herd of cattle, a class of pupils. The richness of nouns in a language reflects the richness of the world it describes.\n\nVerbs are the action words of language—they bring sentences to life. Without a verb, a sentence cannot exist. Action verbs describe physical or mental actions: run, jump, think, write, sing, dream. Linking verbs connect the subject to a description: is, am, are, was, were, seem, feel. Auxiliary (helping) verbs work alongside main verbs to show tense or possibility: can, will, should, have, must. Every complete sentence must contain at least one verb.\n\nIdentifying nouns and verbs in sentences is a skill that develops with practice. In the sentence 'The children play in the garden,' 'children' and 'garden' are nouns, and 'play' is the verb. In 'The teacher writes on the board,' 'teacher' and 'board' are nouns, and 'writes' is the verb. Practising this identification in real sentences builds grammatical awareness and helps learners construct their own sentences more accurately.\n\nNouns and verbs must agree in number. A singular noun takes a singular verb, and a plural noun takes a plural verb. We say 'The dog runs' (singular) but 'The dogs run' (plural). This agreement is called subject-verb agreement, and it is one of the most important grammar rules in English. Errors in subject-verb agreement are among the most common mistakes in writing, so understanding this rule early is very valuable.\n\nVerbs also change form to show tense—when an action happens. The present tense describes what is happening now: 'She sings.' The past tense describes what happened before: 'She sang.' The future tense describes what will happen: 'She will sing.' Understanding verb tenses allows writers to place events in time accurately and tell stories in a clear, logical sequence.\n\nNouns can be modified by adjectives (describing words) to give more information: 'a tall tree,' 'a happy child,' 'three red apples.' Verbs can be modified by adverbs to show how, when, or where an action happens: 'She ran quickly,' 'He arrived yesterday,' 'They played outside.' These modifications make language more precise and expressive.\n\nA deep understanding of nouns and verbs is the gateway to all other grammar knowledge. Once learners can confidently identify and use nouns and verbs, they are ready to explore adjectives, adverbs, pronouns, prepositions, and conjunctions. Grammar is not a set of arbitrary rules—it is the system that makes language work, and nouns and verbs are at the very heart of that system.",
