    id: "eng-3", subjectId: "english", emoji: "🔍", readMins: 8,
    title: "Comprehension",
    summary: "Comprehension is the ultimate goal of reading. It is not enough to be able to decode words—to sound them out and pronounce them correctly. True reading means understanding what those words mean, how they connect to each other, and what message the writer is trying to communicate. Comprehension is the bridge between the marks on a page and the meaning in the reader's mind, and developing strong comprehension skills is one of the most important things a learner can do.\n\nGood comprehension begins before the reading even starts. Previewing a text—looking at the title, headings, pictures, and any bold or highlighted words—activates prior knowledge and prepares the brain for the topic. This pre-reading strategy helps learners make predictions about what they will read, which keeps them engaged and makes the content easier to understand and remember.\n\nAs learners read, they should be actively thinking about the text rather than passively moving their eyes across the page. Active reading involves asking questions: Who are the characters? What is happening? Why did that happen? What might happen next? These questions keep the mind engaged and help the reader monitor their own understanding. If a question cannot be answered, it is a signal to re-read that section more carefully.\n\nVocabulary is closely linked to comprehension. When a reader encounters too many unfamiliar words, understanding breaks down. Context clues—the words and sentences surrounding an unknown word—can often reveal its meaning. For example, if a text says 'The parched traveller desperately searched for water,' the context makes it clear that 'parched' means very thirsty. Learning to use context clues is a powerful strategy for independent reading.\n\nFinding the main idea is a central comprehension skill. Every paragraph and every text has a main idea—the most important point the writer is making. Supporting details provide evidence, examples, or explanations for the main idea. Being able to distinguish between main ideas and supporting details helps learners summarize texts accurately and understand the structure of arguments and explanations.\n\nInference is a higher-level comprehension skill that involves reading between the lines. Sometimes writers do not state everything directly—they expect the reader to use clues in the text combined with their own knowledge to draw conclusions. For example, if a story says 'Maria put on her raincoat and picked up her umbrella,' the reader can infer that it is raining or about to rain, even though this is not stated directly. Developing inference skills transforms a basic reader into a sophisticated one.\n\nSummarizing is the ability to retell the main points of a text in your own words, leaving out unnecessary details. A good summary captures the essential meaning of a text concisely and accurately. Summarizing requires the reader to have understood the text deeply enough to distinguish what is important from what is not. It is one of the best ways to check and consolidate comprehension.\n\nComprehension skills developed in the early years of schooling have a profound impact on academic success across all subjects. Science, social studies, mathematics, and every other subject require learners to read and understand texts. A learner who reads with strong comprehension is better equipped to learn independently, think critically, and succeed in every area of their education. Comprehension is not just a reading skill—it is a thinking skill.",
