    id: "eng-4", subjectId: "english", emoji: "❗", readMins: 8,
    title: "Punctuation",
    summary: "Punctuation is the system of marks and symbols that writers use to organize their writing and guide their readers. Without punctuation, written language would be a confusing stream of words with no clear boundaries between sentences, no indication of questions or exclamations, and no pauses to help the reader breathe and process meaning. Punctuation is to writing what traffic signals are to roads—it keeps everything moving smoothly and safely.\n\nCapital letters are one of the most fundamental punctuation conventions. Every sentence must begin with a capital letter, signaling to the reader that a new thought is starting. Proper nouns—the names of specific people, places, days, months, and titles—always begin with capital letters. The word 'I' is always written as a capital. These rules are not optional; they are the basic conventions that all writers must follow to be understood.\n\nThe full stop (.) is the most common end punctuation mark. It signals the end of a statement—a sentence that tells something. Without full stops, sentences would run together endlessly, making text impossible to read. The full stop tells the reader: this thought is complete; pause here before moving on. Learning to place full stops correctly is one of the first and most important punctuation skills.\n\nThe question mark (?) ends any sentence that asks a question. It signals to the reader that the sentence is seeking information or a response. Questions are a fundamental part of communication—we use them to learn, to clarify, to engage in conversation, and to express curiosity. Recognizing when a sentence is a question and marking it correctly with a question mark is an essential writing skill.\n\nThe exclamation mark (!) is used to show strong emotion, surprise, excitement, or urgency. 'Watch out!' 'What a beautiful day!' 'I won!' These sentences carry emotional weight that a full stop cannot convey. However, exclamation marks should be used sparingly—if every sentence ends with one, the effect is lost. Good writers save exclamation marks for moments of genuine emphasis.\n\nThe comma (,) is one of the most versatile and frequently used punctuation marks. It separates items in a list: 'I bought bread, milk, eggs, and butter.' It separates clauses in a sentence: 'Although it was raining, we went outside.' It follows introductory phrases: 'After school, we played football.' Commas signal a brief pause and help the reader understand the structure and meaning of complex sentences.\n\nApostrophes (') have two main uses. They show possession: 'the dog's bone' means the bone belonging to the dog. They also show contraction—where letters have been left out: 'don't' is short for 'do not,' and 'it's' is short for 'it is.' Apostrophes are small but powerful marks that change the meaning of words significantly.\n\nMastering punctuation is a gradual process that develops through reading and writing practice. The more learners read well-punctuated texts, the more naturally they absorb the conventions. The more they write and receive feedback on their punctuation, the more accurate they become. Correct punctuation is a sign of a careful, considerate writer—one who respects their reader enough to make their writing as clear and easy to understand as possible.",
