    id: "env-2", subjectId: "environmental", emoji: "⛅", readMins: 7,
    title: "Weather and Seasons",
    summary: "Weather is one of the most immediate and observable aspects of the natural world. Every day, the weather affects what we wear, what we eat, how we travel, and what activities we can do. Understanding weather—what causes it, how it changes, and how it affects our lives—is one of the most practical and fascinating areas of environmental science that young learners can explore.\n\nWeather describes the condition of the atmosphere at a particular place and time. It includes temperature (how hot or cold it is), precipitation (rain, hail, or snow), wind (how fast the air is moving and in which direction), humidity (how much moisture is in the air), and cloud cover (how much of the sky is covered by clouds). All of these elements combine to create the weather we experience each day.\n\nTemperature is measured using a thermometer, which shows how hot or cold the air is in degrees Celsius (°C). On a hot sunny day in Kenya, the temperature might reach 30°C or more. On a cool morning in the highlands, it might be as low as 10°C. Understanding temperature helps us dress appropriately, plan activities, and understand why different regions have different climates.\n\nKenya has a varied climate due to its diverse geography. The coastal regions are hot and humid. The highlands around Nairobi and Mount Kenya are cooler. The northern regions are hot and dry. This diversity means that different parts of Kenya experience different weather patterns, and understanding these patterns is important for farming, tourism, and daily life.\n\nKenya has two main rainy seasons. The long rains, known as masika in Kiswahili, fall from March to May. The short rains, known as vuli, fall from October to December. Between these rainy seasons are dry periods. These seasonal patterns are crucial for farmers, who plan their planting and harvesting around the rains. Understanding the seasons helps communities prepare for both the abundance of the rainy season and the challenges of the dry season.\n\nWeather affects agriculture profoundly. Crops need water to grow, and in Kenya, most farming depends on rainfall rather than irrigation. When the rains come on time and in sufficient amounts, harvests are good and food is plentiful. When rains fail or come too late, crops suffer and food becomes scarce. This is why weather forecasting is so important for farming communities.\n\nWeather also affects health. Hot, humid conditions can promote the spread of diseases like malaria, as mosquitoes breed in standing water left by rain. Cold, dry conditions can increase respiratory illnesses. Flooding during heavy rains can contaminate water sources and spread waterborne diseases. Understanding the relationship between weather and health helps communities take preventive measures.\n\nClimate change is altering weather patterns around the world, including in Kenya. Rains are becoming less predictable, droughts are more frequent, and extreme weather events are more common. Understanding weather and climate is therefore not just an academic exercise—it is essential knowledge for communities that need to adapt to a changing world and protect their livelihoods and health.",
