    id: "hyg-3", subjectId: "hygiene", emoji: "🦠", readMins: 7,
    title: "Disease Prevention",
    summary: "Disease prevention is one of the most important aspects of public health and personal wellbeing. The old saying 'prevention is better than cure' captures a profound truth: it is far better—and far easier—to stop a disease from occurring than to treat it after it has taken hold. Understanding how diseases spread, what causes them, and how to protect ourselves and our communities is knowledge that can literally save lives.\n\nGerms are the microscopic organisms that cause infectious diseases. They are too small to see with the naked eye, but they are everywhere—on surfaces, in the air, in water, and in food. There are four main types of germs: bacteria (single-celled organisms that can cause diseases like tuberculosis, typhoid, and cholera), viruses (even smaller than bacteria, causing diseases like flu, measles, and COVID-19), fungi (causing conditions like ringworm and athlete's foot), and parasites (organisms that live in or on a host, causing diseases like malaria and intestinal worms).\n\nUnderstanding how germs spread is the key to preventing disease. Airborne transmission occurs when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or breathes, releasing tiny droplets containing germs into the air. Diseases like flu, measles, and tuberculosis spread this way. Waterborne transmission occurs when germs contaminate water sources, causing diseases like cholera, typhoid, and diarrhoea when people drink or use the contaminated water. Contact transmission occurs when germs are transferred through direct contact with an infected person or contaminated surface.\n\nHandwashing is the single most effective way to prevent the spread of many infectious diseases. Germs on our hands can enter our bodies when we touch our faces, eat food, or prepare meals. Washing hands thoroughly with soap and water removes these germs before they can cause harm. The World Health Organization identifies five critical moments for handwashing: before eating, before preparing food, after using the toilet, after handling animals, and after coughing or sneezing.\n\nVaccination is one of the greatest achievements of modern medicine. Vaccines train the immune system to recognize and fight specific pathogens without causing the disease itself. Vaccines have eliminated or dramatically reduced diseases that once killed millions of people, including smallpox, polio, and measles. In Kenya, the national immunization program provides vaccines against many serious diseases, including tuberculosis, polio, measles, and hepatitis B. Ensuring that children receive all recommended vaccines is one of the most important things parents can do to protect their children's health.\n\nMalaria is one of the most serious diseases in Kenya and across sub-Saharan Africa. It is caused by a parasite called Plasmodium, which is transmitted through the bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. Malaria causes fever, chills, headache, and in severe cases can be fatal, especially in young children. Prevention measures include sleeping under insecticide-treated mosquito nets, using mosquito repellent, eliminating standing water where mosquitoes breed, and taking antimalarial medication when recommended.\n\nFood safety is another important aspect of disease prevention. Foodborne illnesses are caused by eating food contaminated with bacteria, viruses, parasites, or toxins. Proper food handling—washing hands before preparing food, cooking food thoroughly, storing food at safe temperatures, and avoiding cross-contamination between raw and cooked foods—significantly reduces the risk of foodborne illness. In Kenya, where many people eat street food or food prepared in informal settings, food safety awareness is particularly important.\n\nDisease prevention is a shared responsibility. When individuals take steps to protect their own health, they also protect the health of their families and communities. When communities work together to improve sanitation, ensure access to clean water, and promote vaccination, they create environments where diseases struggle to spread. Understanding disease prevention from an early age empowers young people to make choices that protect their health and contribute to the health of their communities.",
