    id: "hyg-4", subjectId: "hygiene", emoji: "💧", readMins: 7,
    title: "Clean Water and Sanitation",
    summary: "Access to clean water and proper sanitation are among the most fundamental human rights and the most powerful determinants of public health. Water is essential for life—every cell in the human body requires water to function. We need it for drinking, cooking, bathing, and growing food. When water is contaminated or sanitation is poor, the consequences for health can be devastating. Understanding the importance of clean water and sanitation, and knowing how to ensure both, is knowledge that can save lives.\n\nWater covers about 71% of the Earth's surface, but only about 3% of it is fresh water, and much of that is locked in glaciers and ice caps. The fresh water available for human use is a precious and finite resource. In many parts of Kenya and Africa, access to clean water is a daily challenge. Women and children often walk long distances to collect water, and the water they collect may not be safe to drink. This reality makes water conservation and water safety education critically important.\n\nContaminated water is one of the world's leading causes of illness and death. When water sources are polluted with human or animal waste, industrial chemicals, or other contaminants, they become breeding grounds for dangerous pathogens. Waterborne diseases—including cholera, typhoid fever, dysentery, and diarrhoea—kill hundreds of thousands of people every year, the majority of them children under five. In Kenya, diarrhoeal diseases remain a leading cause of child mortality, and most cases are linked to unsafe water and poor sanitation.\n\nBoiling water is the most reliable method for making it safe to drink. When water is brought to a rolling boil for at least one minute, the heat kills bacteria, viruses, and parasites that cause waterborne diseases. After boiling, the water should be stored in a clean, covered container to prevent re-contamination. In areas where fuel for boiling is scarce, water purification tablets or solar disinfection (leaving water in clear plastic bottles in direct sunlight) are effective alternatives.\n\nProper sanitation—the safe management of human waste—is equally important for public health. Open defecation, the practice of defecating in the open rather than in a toilet or latrine, contaminates soil and water sources with pathogens that cause disease. When people use toilets or latrines and wash their hands afterward, the cycle of fecal-oral disease transmission is broken. Building and using proper sanitation facilities is one of the most effective public health interventions available.\n\nHandwashing with soap after using the toilet is one of the most critical hygiene behaviors for preventing disease. Fecal matter contains enormous numbers of pathogens, and hands contaminated with fecal matter can transfer these pathogens to food, water, and other people. Studies have shown that handwashing with soap can reduce diarrhoeal disease by up to 47% and respiratory infections by up to 23%. This simple, inexpensive practice has an enormous impact on public health.\n\nWater conservation is increasingly important as populations grow and climate change affects rainfall patterns. Simple conservation practices—turning off taps when not in use, fixing leaking pipes, collecting rainwater, using water-efficient irrigation methods, and reusing grey water for gardening—can significantly reduce water consumption. Teaching children to value and conserve water from an early age helps build a culture of water stewardship that will be essential in the decades ahead.\n\nClean water and sanitation are not just health issues—they are development issues. When children are sick from waterborne diseases, they miss school. When women spend hours collecting water, they have less time for education and economic activities. When communities lack proper sanitation, they face stigma and reduced quality of life. Improving access to clean water and sanitation is therefore one of the most powerful ways to promote health, education, gender equality, and economic development simultaneously.",
